After his success at the Ateneo, José Rizal continued his studies at the University of Santo Tomas, one of the oldest university in Asia.
He initially took Philosophy and Letters, before shifting to a Medicine course to help his mother, who was gradually losing her eyesight.
But he found a different world at University of Santo Thomas.
Inside the classroom, he experienced strict and antiquated teaching methods. There were some professors who did not treat Filipino students equally.
Gradually, Rizal felt the weight of discrimination and the difference in treatment between the Indios and the Spaniards.
Here, a deeper truth began to become clear to him that injustice was not only in the fields of Calamba, but also within the educational institutions of the colony.
In his desire for freer learning and more just opportunities, he decided to continue his studies abroad.
And this decision would bring him to a new chapter of his life.